
J Servlet and JSP

Servlet: is a Java program that runs on a server and is used to handle web requests and responses. It is part of Java’s server-side web development.
Think of a servlet as the bridge between a client (browser/postman) and your server-side logic.

Why Do We Need Servlets?
Before frameworks like Spring, Java web apps were built directly using Servlets.
Servelts help with:

Handling browser requests
Processing data from forms
Generating dynamic content
Managing sessions/cookies
Connecting UI to backend logic

How Spring Boot relates to Servlets?
Spring Boot hides servlets from you by providing:

Controllers (@RestController)
Embedded servlet container (Tomcat)
DispatcherServlet (central controller)

Under the hood, Spring MVC still uses servlets — just more advanced and easy to use.





-----------------------------
DispatcherServlet is the front controller in Spring MVC.
It sits at the front of your application and handles every incoming HTTP request before it reaches your controllers.
Think of it as a traffic controller:

Receives all requests
Decides where to send them
Executes controller logic
Prepares and sends the response

Without it, Spring MVC would not work.


------------------
What is an Embedded Servlet Container (Tomcat)?
An embedded servlet container is a built‑in web server that runs inside your Spring Boot application.
The most common one is Tomcat, but Spring Boot can also use Jetty or Undertow.
In simple words:
👉 You don’t install Tomcat separately.
👉 Tomcat is packaged inside your Spring Boot jar.
👉 When you run your application, Tomcat starts automatically.









